Anonymous Tue 05 Jul 2022 16:46:12 No.49078194 Report
Quoted By: >>49078367 >>49083147
>>49077814
Whether they do or don’t is up to the artist.

If you're going to argue that anthros would've de-evolved their scent glands, then you can just as easily argue that organic anthros wouldn't have snouts. Humans evolved flat faces in order to handle punches to the face by other humans. To compete with humanity (so as to not have gone extinct by the modern era), anthros would have also needed to form large social groups or tribes of some kind. But there would inevitably be in-fighting and a need to inflict long-range damage without making your neck vulnerable (things that biting can't accomplish). Punching, kicking, and throwing projectiles inevitably becomes more viable.
Having a snout would be a terrible disadvantage in a world where you will get punched in the face. It's a fragile thing, a snout. It's a crucial part of breathing and eating, but it breaks incredibly easily because extended noses have less structural integrity. It's easier to apply torque on things that stick out.
Perhaps "organically-evolved" anthros would look more like kemonos, then.
